'''Tzizvvt''' was a [[Gender/Legends|male]] [[Brizzit]] who hailed from [[Jandoon]]. Claiming to be a professor of [[Archaeology/Legends|xenoarchaeology]] searching for a treasure known as "[[The Eye of the Beyonder]]," he was believed to be a fugitive from the [[Galactic Empire/Legends|Galactic Empire]] named '''Ilna'''. Setting up residence in [[Tatooine/Legends|Tatooine's]] sewers, Tzizvvt soon became a figure of derision on the [[Planet/Legends|planet]], dismissed as a "crazy old storyteller." He had in fact collected some treasures, which he kept in his sewer-bound residence, but kept them secret from the proletarians.

The [[Lutrillian/Legends|Lutrillian]] war veteran [[Solomahal/Legends|Solomahal]] was one of the few who paid attention to Tzizvvt's stories told in [[Chalmun's Spaceport Cantina/Legends|Chalmun's Spaceport Cantina]], and although he was not utterly convinced of the Brizzit's honesty, he was interested enough to inquire further. Impressed by Tzizvvt's collection, he agreed to help him search for his elusive treasure, even without up-front payment by the Brizzit.

==Biography==
===Tatooine===
Tzizvvt, a native of [[Jandoon]], was a member of the [[Brizzit]] [[Species/Legends|species]]. Despite the fact that [[Human/Legends|Humans]] found distinguishing different Brizzits difficult, Tzizvvt was listed on the [[Galactic Empire/Legends|Imperial]] [[HoloNet/Legends|HoloNet]] as "Ilna", a fugitive from Imperial justice who had stolen valuable relics from [[Biitu]] and [[Roon/Legends|Roon]].<ref name="db" /> In an attempt to elude capture, he journeyed to [[Tatooine/Legends|Tatooine]], where he hoped to find a [[Pilot/Legends|pilot]] who would ferry him to safety.<ref name="ccg">{{CCG|set=A New Hope Limited|cardname=Tzizvvt}}</ref>

Suspicious and fearful, Tzizvvt masqueraded as a [[Xenoarchaeology/Legends|xenoarchaeology]] professor, who sought an artifact known as [[The Eye of the Beyonder]]. [[File:SolomahalTzizvvt.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Tzizvvt and [[Atheloe]].]]Telling his story to those who would listen, he became a well known figure amongst the [[Mos Eisley/Legends|Mos Eisley]] locals, and "crazy old" Tzizvvt soon earned the derision of the [[City/Legends|city's]] spacefaring populace. He took up residence in Tatooine's antiquated sewers, and filled his quarters with the stolen treasures from Biitu and Roon. He also kept a particularly spectacular piece, purported to have come from Jandoon itself.<ref name="db" />

===Solomahal===
In [[0 BBY/Legends|0 BBY]], Tzivvt was present in [[Chalmun's Spaceport Cantina/Legends|Chalmun's Spaceport Cantina]] when an elderly man entered the building with a younger man and a [[C-3PO/Legends|golden protocol droid]]. The younger man, [[Farmer/Legends|farmboy]] [[Luke Skywalker/Legends|Luke Skywalker]], got into an argument with the [[Aqualish/Legends|Aqualish]] thug [[Ponda Baba/Legends|Ponda Baba]], and the older [[Human/Legends|Human]], [[Jedi Master/Legends|Jedi Master]] [[Obi-Wan Kenobi/Legends|Obi-Wan Kenobi]], interjected and used his [[Obi-Wan Kenobi's third lightsaber/Legends|lightsaber]] to slice off one of the Aqualish's [[Limb/Legends|arms]]. Although the spectacle initially grabbed everyone's attention, most went back to their conversations after several moments. The crowd then collectively turned to witness Kenobi depart the [[Cantina/Legends|cantina]].<ref name="anh">{{Film|IV}}</ref> Eventually, word of Tzizvvt's tales reached the [[Ear/Legends|ears]] of [[Solomahal/Legends|Solomahal]], a veteran [[General/Legends|General]] of the [[Clone Wars/Legends|Clone Wars]]. The Brizzit met the [[Lutrillian/Legends|Lutrillian]] in the cantina, where Tzizvvt spun his requisite tale about "The Eye of the Beyonder." Solomahal was skeptical, and privately investigated the Brizzit's background. Despite his discovery of the Imperial warrant, he was still interested, and contacted Tzizvvt in his sewer residence. The Brizzit could not pay for Solomahal's services as a pilot up front, but the Lutrillian agreed to provide passage for him, in exchange for a cut of the treasures that would hypothetically be retrieved.<ref name="db" />

==Personality and traits==
Adept at spinning a tale and covering his identity, Tzizvvt was able to successfully evade Imperial reprisal for a [[Time/Legends|time]] leading up to the [[Battle of Yavin/Legends|Battle of Yavin]]. He developed an identity for himself in the Mos Eisley community, and was regarded as nothing more than a storyteller who was liberal with the truth. Some even went so far as to label him "crazy." Nonetheless, he was eventually able to convince a pilot to aid him, even without the presentation of [[Galactic Credit Standard/Legends|credits]] prior to service.<ref name="db" />

==Behind the scenes==
[[File:Brizzitmarvel.jpg|thumb|150px|The Brizzit shown in [[Star Wars (1977) 2|''Star Wars'' (1977) 2]].]]
{{Quote|My entry had a very open ending and I liked that. Their adventure was just about to begin! A short story or comic could even be written about that adventure.|[[Tim Veekhoven]]|<ref name="blog" />}}
The character of Tzizvvt first appeared in [[1977]]'s [[Star Wars: Episode IV A New Hope|''Star Wars'': Episode IV ''A New Hope'']], as an unnamed alien in the Cantina sequence. On the set of the film, the character was known as "Snail Head," and was supposed to have been given the proper name of "Illna." The character was largely edited out of the film following re-shoots, but still appears fleetingly in the final cut.<ref name="crc">{{SWArchive|url=episode-iv/bts/article/f20030502/index.html|text=Cantina Roll-Call: Shedding Light on Some Alien Aliases|int=Cantina Roll-Call: Shedding Light on Some Alien Aliases}}</ref> A character of the same species appeared in the second issue of [[Marvel Comics]]' adaptation of ''A New Hope'', [[Star Wars (1977) 2|''Star Wars'' (1977) 2]], published fifteen days prior to the film's release.<ref name="tcr">[[Wikipedia:The Comic Reader|''The Comic Reader'']] #143, provided by Marvel</ref> Whether or not this is intended to be the character that would become Tzizvvt is unconfirmed. The intended "Illna" name was forgotten or ignored by [[Decipher]] when they identified the character as "Tzizvvt" in the [[Star Wars Customizable Card Game|''Star Wars'' Customizable Card Game]].
[[File:Tzizvvt_concept_art.jpg|thumb|left|A sketch of Tzizvvt was drawn by John Mollo.|200px]]
Tzizvvt's backstory was established by [[Tim Veekhoven]] through [[Hyperspace: The Official Star Wars Fan Club|Hyperspace's]] "[[What's The Story?]]" feature. The original entry had elaborated further on [[The Eye of the Beyonder]], and had established "Illna" as the Brizzit homeworld, but these elements were either omitted or modified for the final entry. Veekhoven was inspired by the [[Wikipedia:Indiana Jones|Indiana Jones]] films and the comic [[Star Wars (1977) 84|''Star Wars'' 84]] while writing Tzizvvt's backstory.<ref name="blog">{{Blog|teekay-421|13|They were the chosen ones}}</ref> Information from Veekhoven's entry was later used for the character's entry in [[2008]]'s ''[[The Complete Star Wars Encyclopedia]]''.

A sheet of sketched designs for cantina characters by costume designer [[John Mollo]] included Tzizvvt under the title of "Fly", with annotations describing the character as having wide shoulders and a white [[Belt/Legends|belt]] and [[Holster/Legends|holster]]. "[[Stephen Calcutt|Stephen Culcutt]]" was also written as a suggestion of who might play the character, but was crossed through.<ref name="TAoSW">''[[The Art of Star Wars Episode IV: A New Hope]]'' {{C|page 60}}</ref>

